mme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Asia-Pacific GEM: Quarterly Newsletter on Gender and Macroeconomic Issues", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/asia-pacific-gem-quarterly-newsletter-gender-and-macroeconomic-issues", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "136834337fb112a4780cbdba6612c0736a2ce302560d44e721b655fcb7d5021c"}, "3": {"node_id": "0bb602e8-b572-4961-82bf-4d81186c6e9d", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/asia-pacific-gem-quarterly-newsletter-gender-and-macroeconomic-issues", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0f7c99c9bfc5b3032cc06191036442fe7f195fd848830cb6054e28c1b0a9a4a3"}}, "hash": "be8bbbd472e9a4813d1dfef23f5b1cb488c8da37138fc499f9a799fcfd483c92", "text": "1 Asia-Pacific GEM Inside this issue: Quarterly Newsletter on Gender and Macroeconomic Issues (GEM) in Asia and the Pacific March 2014 Volume 5, Issue 1 Asian Conference on Gender Responsive Budgeting in Penang Being offered for the very first time in Viet Nam, training courses on gender and economic policy making have received enormous success. Cours- es, based on the UNDP\u2019s training modules on Gender Economic Policy Management, were customized to respond to the needs of the Gov- ernment of Viet Nam. Two participatory training courses were held back-to-back in Hanoi to accommodate a huge demand. The first training programme \u201cGender Responsive Economics and Social Protection\u201d was delivered to 23 researchers of the Institute of Family and Gender Studies (IFGS), a leading research institute based in Hanoi, on February 10-15, 2014. Social protection plays a funda- mental role in creating inclusive and sustainable development. It helps in tackling multiple di- mensions of poverty and deprivation through the provision of decent work, education, health care, food and income security. It can therefore be a powerful tool in the battle against poverty and inequality. Women are the poorest of the poor and the ones to suffer the most due to lack of social security nets and access thereof. In the absence of adequate social protection they are subjected to increased risks of sinking below the poverty line or remaining trapped in pov- erty for generations. [continued on page 2] Gender and Economic Policy Making Training in Viet Nam 1-2 Asian Conference on Gender Responsive Budgeting in Penang 1-3 Call for Participation South Asian Conference on Women, Work and Poverty, April 17-19, 2014 Workshop on Researching Women and Society in Pe- nang, August 15, 2014 3 New Resources: Humanity Divided: Con- fronting Inequality in Devel- oping Countries Feminist Economists Re- spond to the IMF Discussion Note \u201cWomen, Work and the Economy\u201d 4 Call for Papers/ Call for Applications: The 2014 Rhonda Williams Prize\u2014Application deadline extended to April 4, 2014 Postgraduate International Conference on Gender Stud- ies, August 13-14, 2014\u2014 Application deadline is March 31, 2014 5 About Us: UNDP Asia-Pacific Regional Centre 5 The Asian Regional Conference entitled Gender Responsive Budgeting Narratives: Transform- ing Institutions, Empowering Communities took place on February 24-25, in Penang, Malaysia. This ground-breaking event brought together an impressive range of speakers, chairs and facilitators from across the region and indeed around the world, including from Austria, Ger- many, and Portugal. Presentations were made to over 300 participants and importantly in- cluded attendees from the two local municipal councils in Penang. The presentations and discussions over the two days centred on the current role and impact of Gender Responsive Budg- eting (GRB) within national, state/ provincial and local government institu- tions, and how it is increasingly being linked to opening up the processes of budgeting to more directly include and empower women and men in local communities. This framed a discussion of two aspects. Firstly, certain sessions focused on the changing nature of budget planning and nar- rated practical examples of how the collection and use of data is providing a series of oppor- tunities for GRB. Secondly, there was focus also on the relationship between GRB and par- ticipatory budgeting, and the extent to which empowerment of communities is, can or should be a central concern of GRB. As the discussions unfolded, it became clear that national and local governments across the region have been changing their budgeting processes in ways that [continued on page 3] Gender and Economic Policy Making Training in Viet Nam YB Chong Eng, Chair of the Penang Women\u2019s Development Corporation (PWDC) and Penang State Exco for Youth and Sports, Women, Family and Community Development, speaking at the Conference. Participants of the training course \u201cGender Responsive Economics and Social Protection,\u201d February 10-15, 2014 2 Asia-Pacific GEM Vol. 5 Issue 1 Both courses were led by Professor Ha- roon Akram-Lohdi, Chair, Department of International Development Studies, Trent University, Canada. The courses were offered in English with simultaneous translation to Vietnamese. The UNDP training modules has been developed to respond to the urgent need of incorporating gender perspectives into national development frameworks.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "0bb602e8-b572-4961-82bf-4d81186c6e9d": {"__data__": {"id_": "0bb602e8-b572-4961-82bf-4d81186c6e9d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.o