re, social entitle- ments and social justice; law, policy and gender; patriarchy, the family and femi- nist discourses; sexuality, masculinity and identity politics; sustainable development and environmental issues; violence against women; and women, leadership and the political process. Postgraduate students and young schol- ars who have obtained their Master\u2019s or PhD degrees within two years prior to the date of the conference are welcome to submit abstracts (450 words) at kanita.kpicgs@gmail.com by March 31, 2014. Interested individuals who do not submit papers may also attend as partici- pants. Malaysian Ringgit (RM) 80 for partici- pants affiliated with local institutions and USD40 otherwise apply for registration before May 31, 2014. Registration fee will be increased to RM 100 and USD 50 re- spectively after June 1. Fees will cover all meals and materials during the Confer- ence. Participants are responsible for their own accommodation and travel arrangements. For more information, please visit the conference website. *Contributed, with thanks, by KANITA, USM+", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "239e6347-6ab2-4887-a187-98df6b3e9eb6": {"__data__": {"id_": "239e6347-6ab2-4887-a187-98df6b3e9eb6", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/assessing-gender-responsive-local-capacity-development-indonesia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Assessing gender responsive local capacity development in Indonesia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/assessing-gender-responsive-local-capacity-development-indonesia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "719bb2654001c77381263cc66c2e2189bc5515025e8bb86797fe3494ef791917"}, "3": {"node_id": "2d652f81-478b-4124-b017-ba8d68da4786", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/assessing-gender-responsive-local-capacity-development-indonesia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "92939eed6f7208e6b0a2750663a4fb4455649053a3fb8ca344d9b335159c5438"}}, "hash": "4ec3e4ec7f2ff453189a6efad312c9e244b7ba1f77cc0e1c6eeabef83ca21c66", "text": "II The analysis and recommendations of this report do not necessarily reflect the official views of the United Nations Development Programme. UNDP is the UN\u2019s global development network, advocating for change and connecting countries to knowledge, experience and resources to help people build a better life. United Nations Development Programme Regional Centre in Bangkok 3rd Floor, UN Service Building Rajdamnern Nok Avenue Bangkok, 10200, Thailand Website: http://regionalcentrebangkok.undp.or.th/ Copyright \u00a9 UNDP 2009 ISBN: 978-974-680-263-5 March 2009 Photos: \u00a9Reuters and UNDP Editing and design by In\u00eds Communication \u2013 www.inis.ie The United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) believes that gender equality is central to sustained human development, and considers it vital to integrate women\u2019s empowerment and gender equality into the organization\u2019s core business. This is done through two complementary approaches: i) gender mainstreaming, and ii) promoting women\u2019s empowerment. The development of capacity (both of country stakeholders and in-house staff) to integrate gender concerns in core areas of development work is a vital element of successfully engendering UNDP\u2019s agenda. The UNDP 2008\u20132011 Strategic Plan likewise emphasizes that capacity development is UNDP\u2019s \u2018overarching contribution\u2019 to global human development efforts. Thus, gender responsiveness in capacity development interventions is a critical element for overall development effectiveness. It is in this sense that the two cross-cutting areas of UNDP\u2019s mandate work in a mutually reinforcing manner. The Netherlands Development Organization (SNV) is a Netherlands-based international NGO that delivers capacity development advisory services to over 2,000 clients in 32 countries worldwide. In Asia, SNV provides capacity development services to government, non- government and private-sector organizations in Bangladesh, Bhutan, Cambodia, the Lao People\u2019s Democratic Republic, Nepal and Viet Nam, as well as to a number of regional networks. SNV\u2019s 140 advisors in Asia work with local capacity builders and local actors \u2013 primarily those who operate at national and meso levels \u2013 in strengthening their capacity to effectively realize poverty reduction and good governance. For more information about SNV, visit: www.snvworld.org. Acknowledegments The United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) acknowledges the significant contribution of Leya Cattleya, lead author and researcher, to this report. UNDP also recognizes Danielle Noble for her editorial work on this publication. Special thanks go to Elena Tischenko and Yanti Lacsana from the UNDP Indonesia country office for their review and support of the study. Finally, this publication has benefited greatly from the input of all UNDP colleagues who generously shared their experience and expertise for both the content and review. The contributions of the following UNDP staff are gratefully acknowledged: Patricia Alexander, Dipa Bagai, Radhika Behuria, Robert Bernardo, Roohi Metcalfe and Ashley Palmer. contents Foreword VI 1. Introduction 1 1.1 The development context in Indonesia 1 1.2 Definitions 3 2. Gender-responsive local capacity development for accelerating the MD